        </figure>
      

    
  


  





  <p class="">If you happen to be checking out the Vatican City on a Wednesday, and if the pope is in Rome on that day, you might very well get a glimpse of him, so consider attending a <a href="http://www.papalaudience.org/tickets"><span>papal audience</span></a> in St. Peter's Square. This is a unique opportunity to see the Pope in person and receive his blessing.</p><p class="">And the best part? It’s completely FREE! Don’t fall for the scammy tour guides trying to sell you $50+ tickets to the Papal Audience - you don’t have to pay a cent.&nbsp;</p><p class="">When you’re done all that, or perhaps even earlier, you might want to visit the Vatican Gardens, which cover more than half of Vatican City's territory. These are especially useful to see with a guided tour, which provides insights into the history, architecture, and flora of this peaceful oasis.</p><p class="">And of course, you’ll be in awe when - at the end of your journey through the Vatican -, you’ll find yourself standing in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St._Peter%27s_Square"><span>Saint Peter’s Square</span></a>, a gigantic piazza first opened in 1667, and located directly in front of and beneath St. Peter’s Basilica.&nbsp;</p><p class="">The towering columns - of which there are 284 total - supporting the colonnade surrounding the entire plaza are alone worth the price of admission, as you’ll be staring up in awe at them, admiring their gargantuan size, and taking photos like there’s no tomorrow. I know that’s what I did.&nbsp;</p>





















  
  














































  

    
  
    

      

      
